Section 1:

Stationarity Check:

A time series is said to be stationary when mean, variance and autocorrelation do not change over a period of time. If they do, the time series will be assumed to be non stationary . Non stationarity results in problems while forecasting making it harder to predict our next values. Therefore if our data is non stationary which holds true from our further analysis, we need to difference it and make it stationary.

Checking for Stationarity

Global temperature anomalies data is prone to a lot of fluctuations due to a multitude of factors. Pollution levels, green house gases, the pandemic in between could have had a significant impact on our data thereby there being a need to check for stationarity/non stationarity.To confirm non stationarity, plotting rolling averages and rolling standard deviations will be our first step in analysis.

Rolling Average :

Code 
library(zoo)
data_roll <- data_monthly %>%
  mutate(
    close_mean = zoo::rollmean(
      Value, 
      k = 60, 
      fill = NA),
    close_sd = zoo::rollapply(
      Value, 
      FUN = sd, 
      width = 60, 
      fill = NA)
  )

data_rollmean <- data_roll %>%
  ggplot() +
    geom_line(aes(Year, Value)) +
  geom_line(aes(Year, close_mean),color='blue') +
  theme_bw() +
  ggtitle("Mean of Global Temp Anomalies over time") +
  ylab("Temperature Anomalies") +
  xlab("Time")

data_rollmean

The above plot tells us that the mean is not stationary because it is not constant , confirming our assumptions.

From the above observations, both box-cox and log transformations are doing good job at making the data variance stationary.

Log transformation reduces variance greatly compared to Box-Cox transformation. So log transformation is preferred over Box-Cox in our case

Section 2:

ACF AND PACF

On Original Data :

For a stationary time series, the ACF will drop to zero relatively quickly, while the ACF of non-stationary data decreases slowly. Also, for non-stationary data, the value of correlation is often large and positive.This can be used to infer that our data is non stationary.

We see a dampening effect in our original ACF plot, which indicates that it could be an Auto regressive or AR process , the PACF plot has two statistically significant lags which indicates that our model could be an AR process of order 2. ARIMA(2,1,0)

Code 
ACF1=acf(data_monthly$Value) %>%
  autoplot()
Code 
PACF1=pacf(data_monthly$Value) %>%
  autoplot()

On transformed series:

Code 
acf = data_diff %>%
  ACF(data_log_diff_up,lag_max=10, na.action = na.pass) %>%
  autoplot()

pacf =  data_diff %>%
  fill_gaps() %>%
  PACF(data_log_diff_up) %>%
  autoplot()

acf + pacf

From the ACF plot, it is observed that there is no dampening affect, which means that our time series could be an MA process. Since, it is an MA/Moving Averages process, looking at the statistically significant lag in the ACF plot gives the order of the moving average process. We observe that there are three statistically significant lags - so it could be an ARIMA model of ARIMA(0,1,3)

The process for the log transformed data without the differencing can also be checked using ACF/PACF plots as can be seen below.

Log Transformed Series

Code 
acf_og = data_diff %>%
  as_tsibble()%>%
  ACF(data_log,lag_max=10, na.action = na.pass) %>%
  autoplot()

pacf_og =  data_diff %>%
  as_tsibble()%>%
  fill_gaps() %>%
  PACF(data_log) %>%
  autoplot()

acf_og + pacf_og

For the log transformed series without adding the difference, the ACF plot indicates that there is dampening affect. This indicates that the series is an autoregressive process .There are 3 significant lags in our PACF plot so it could be an AR process of order 2.

We also know that the original series is non stationary and has to differenced twice, one for seasonality and one for the first difference. Therefore, the order of Integration is 1. The original data is ARIMA(2,1,0).

The seasonal aspect of ARIMA can be interpretable from ACF/PACF plots as shown below.

Seasonal

Code 
data_diff %>%
  as_tsibble() %>%
  gg_tsdisplay(difference(data_log,12),
               plot_type='partial', lag=12) +
  labs(title="Seasonally differenced", y="")

Looking at the ACF plot we can infer that the plot is exponentially decaying which indicates an AR or auto regressive process,the PACF plot has two significant lags which implies that it can be an AR process of order 2.Also the integration term is 1, since we are differencing the data once for removing seasonality. The final ARIMA model after taking seasonality into account is ARIMA(2,1,0)(1,1,0).

Fitted Values: In-sample predicted values are based on the data used to fit the model, and may reflect the trends in the transformed data but they donât necessarily capture the underlying trend in the data as a whole. This happens because we use only some part of our data to make predictions and not the entirety of it

Section 4

Residual Diagnostics:

Residual diagnostics help us understand the underlying patterns in our data.We can see that our residuals are normally distributed , so all the patterns in our data are being captured.Our variance seems to follow a constant pattern.

Code 
best_mod %>%
  gg_tsresiduals()

Above plot shows the residual after fitting the best model to our time series.

To check if the selected model is the best model, further analysis on the residuals has to be done. As part of this, Ljung-Box test is performed to find any remaining autocorrelation in the residuals of the best model.

Ljung-Box test

Code 
best_mod %>%
  augment() %>%
  features(.innov, ljung_box, lag = 7, dof = 6)
# A tibble: 1 Ã 3
  .model                                           lb_stat lb_pvalue
  <chr>                                              <dbl>     <dbl>
1 ARIMA(data_log, approximation = F, stepwise = F)    2.77    0.0961

The p-value for Ljung-Box test is 0.09 which greater than 0.05 which implies that our residuals have no remaining autocorrelation.

6 point Forecast:

The 6 point forecast considers substantial parameters into account therefore it seems to be significant.We have used our best model to predict values, thereby cementing the fact that this is as close as we can get to making a proper forecast. But it does remain that the quality of our 6 point forecast has a lot to do with the quality of our data in picture.

Code 
best_mod %>%
  forecast(h=6) %>%
